# SharedMem debug mmap driver

This driver is a debug-only helper for mapping pre-reserved physical shared
memory windows into Linux user space.  It is intended for heterogeneous RTT /
SystemView bring-up, not as a production ownership or security boundary.

The platform must reserve the memory ranges outside the Linux buddy allocator
and configure the inter-core mapping/cache attributes.  For RTT payload access,
the shared memory must be non-cacheable normal memory.

## Build

export KERNEL_BUILD_DIR="/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build"
export SHAREDMEM_DIR="/path/to/SharedMem"
export ARCH="arm64"

make -C "$KERNEL_BUILD_DIR" M="$SHAREDMEM_DIR/Kernel" modules ARCH="$ARCH"

## Docker build from macOS

Docker is supported as a Linux build container for the kernel module.  The
kernel build directory must still come from the target Linux kernel.  Do not use
the Docker VM kernel as the target unless the module will be loaded into that
same kernel.

The host path in `KERNEL_BUILD_DIR` is mounted into the container and passed to
kbuild as the module target:

```sh
export KERNEL_BUILD_DIR="/path/to/target/linux/build"
export ARCH="arm64"

SharedMem/docker/build.sh
```

For ARM32 with a Debian cross toolchain:

```sh
export KERNEL_BUILD_DIR="/path/to/target/linux/build"
export ARCH="arm"
export CROSS_COMPILE="arm-linux-gnueabihf-"
export INSTALL_DEBIAN_CROSS_TOOLCHAINS=1

SharedMem/docker/build.sh
```

For ARM64 with a Debian cross toolchain from an amd64 container:

```sh
export KERNEL_BUILD_DIR="/path/to/target/linux/build"
export ARCH="arm64"
export CROSS_COMPILE="aarch64-linux-gnu-"
export INSTALL_DEBIAN_CROSS_TOOLCHAINS=1
export DOCKER_PLATFORM="linux/amd64"

SharedMem/docker/build.sh
```

For vendor SDK toolchains, mount the SDK and set `CROSS_COMPILE` to the compiler
prefix inside the container:

```sh
export KERNEL_BUILD_DIR="/path/to/target/linux/build"
export SDK_DIR="/path/to/vendor/sdk"
export ARCH="arm"
export CROSS_COMPILE="/work/sdk/path/to/bin/arm-ostl-linux-gnueabi-"

SharedMem/docker/build.sh
```

The generated module is written to:

```text
SharedMem/Kernel/SharedMem.ko
```

## Loading

Single region:

```sh
sudo insmod SharedMem.ko phys_addrs=0x90000000 mem_sizes=0x10000
```

Multiple non-contiguous regions:

```sh
sudo insmod SharedMem.ko \
  phys_addrs=0x90000000,0x91000000 \
  mem_sizes=0x10000,0x20000
```

Multiple non-contiguous regions with one common size:

```sh
sudo insmod SharedMem.ko \
  phys_addrs=0x90000000,0x91000000 \
  mem_sizes=0x10000
```

Multiple contiguous equal-size regions are still passed explicitly:

```sh
sudo insmod SharedMem.ko \
  phys_addrs=0x90000000,0x90010000 \
  mem_sizes=0x10000
```

Each region is exposed as one character device:

- `/dev/shared_mem0`
- `/dev/shared_mem1`
- `/dev/shared_mem2`
- `/dev/shared_mem3`

If `request_mem_region()` fails because the debug range is already owned by a
reserved-memory resource, load with:

```sh
sudo insmod SharedMem.ko phys_addrs=0x90000000 mem_sizes=0x10000 claim_mem_region=0
```

## Constraints

- Every `phys_addrs[]` and `mem_sizes[]` entry must be page-aligned.
- `mmap()` offsets and lengths must be page-aligned.
- All mmap users must use `MAP_SHARED`.
- The driver maps user VMAs with `pgprot_noncached()`, but the platform still
  has to verify the resulting page attributes on the target kernel.
- This driver does not implement cross-core locking.  RTT users still need
  single-writer ownership per ring buffer or a separate cross-core lock.
